    <div id='comments_for_review_4483751' style='display: none;'>
<div class='brown_comment'>
<span class="loadingLinkSpan"><a class="loadingLink" data-remote="true" href="/review/4483751/comments?reverse=true">View all 48 comments</a><span class="loadingAnimation"></span><span class="loadingError"></span></span>
</div>
<div id="comment_228243503" class="brown_comment">
  <div class="xhr_comment_photo">
    	<a alt="Jacqueline Morris" href="/user/show/57545895-jacqueline-morris"><img src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_25x33-ccd24e68f4773d33a41ce08c3a34892e.png" alt="U 25x33" /></a>
  </div>
  <div class="xhr_comment_body">
    <a style="font-weight:bold" href="/user/show/57545895-jacqueline-morris">Jacqueline Morris</a>

      
<span id="freeTextContainer15442226551191433360">Hi there, I’ve been following this with interest because I recently upset a lot of (white) people on a literary forum suggesting The No. 1 Detective A</span>
  <span id="freeText15442226551191433360" style="display:none">Hi there, I’ve been following this with interest because I recently upset a lot of (white) people on a literary forum suggesting The No. 1 Detective Agency was an example of a book that I, as a (white British) reader, found problematic because I didn’t trust the source to give me an authentic vision of Botswana. Oh my goodness! Who knew so many white British people loved these (old) books and would defend to the death A. M. S’s right to write them.<br /><br />I’d originally mentioned the book on this literary forum because I read it and found it a bit - meh. I read a lot of crime fiction. This book would nowadays be called ‘cosy crime’ whereas I’m a reader of the grittier stuff. But it was charming enough to finish, not interesting enough to read on in the series. And it felt odd to read a white man’s interpretation of Botswana using black characters though I wasn’t quite sure why I felt that. Because of the history of colonialism, I guess. Because it seemed bold of him to feel he had the right to do it. But it was a work of fiction and it wasn’t negative, quite the opposite, it seemed, so - well, meh.<br /><br />From the interviews I’ve read I think MS loves Botswana (he wasn’t born there, incidentally, or grew up there, he lived there for a year or so, setting up the University. He grew up in Zimbabwe and went to University in Edinburgh, where he’s lived for a long time now) and his descriptions are lovingly rendered.<br /><br />The reason I find these books problematic now, having read more about it (and massive thanks to Betty above for her perspective which set me off looking) is that they claim to be ‘authentic’ (through their marketing more than anything) and they stand alone in Western culture as an ‘authentic’ representation of Botswana. We Westerners heave a huge sigh of relief and go ‘ah, Africa, so lovely’ the way we do every time we see those Sunday evening programmes like Wild at Heart. And the only other time we really ‘see’ Africa is when there’s an appeal on. I don’t feel like I know real Africa all that well at all (been on a few holidays recently, which helps. I mean, enough to know it’s massive and contains a lot of different countries and people, it’s not just a big blob on the map anymore).<br /><br />I got a lot of the above from reading this: <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.jstor.org/stable/44029511?seq=1">https://www.jstor.org/stable/44029511...</a> though you need an academic account to read all of it (I’m studying with the Open University).<br /><br />Since then I’ve read MS say he likes to write utopian worlds. That’s what this book series is, a simplified utopian world where really bad, complicated stuff doesn’t happen. So, by all means enjoy the charming nature of the books. They’re a bit like Last Of The Summer Wine was for Yorkshire. But read some modern African authors too.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15442226551191433360" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

    <br/>

    <span class="xhrCommentFooter greyText">
      Apr 05, 2021 01:38PM
    </span>

  </div>
  <div class="clear"></div>
</div>
